ogists in Australia -- tPersonal, professional and interprofessional ethics -- tPersonal, professional and interprofessional ethics in policing in a child protection context -- tPersonal, professional and interprofessional ethical issues in the context of supporting children affected by bereavement -- tProfessional and interprofessional ethics in multicultural and multinational contexts -- tFraming the professional and interprofessional ethical landscape in education: Finnish and English perspectives on teachers’ moral selves -- tProfessional and interprofessional cross-cultural ethics in trauma recovery programme implementation by UK professionals in the Middle East -- tSocial work ethics crossing multinational and interprofessional boundaries: smooth passages and bumpy rides -- tPalliative care: the professional and interprofessional ethical considerations for the staff– volunteer interface in the UK and India -- tA way forward? -- tReview of teaching and learning about ethics on a professional training programme for educational psychologists in Scotland -- tProfessionalism in workplace learning: understanding interprofessional dilemmas through healthcare student narratives -- tUnderstanding the dynamics of personal, professional and interprofessional ethics: a possible way forward -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough codes of conduct and ethics provide guidance, professionals have to exercise their own judgement in increasingly complex and demanding roles and work contexts when applying them to practice. At times, this can lead to conflict between personal, professional and interprofessional ethics due to the dynamics of the person-centred environment they function in. This interdisciplinary book draws on the perspectives of 40 authors from four continents to explore the dynamics of ethical dilemmas using theory, research and practice-based examples. Overall, the book will help to spearhead the debate about these ethical dilemmas, and ways of working with them, in an informed manner. It will make ideal reading for students, academics and professionals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aProfessional ethics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aAbdullah, Ghassan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAjjawi, Rola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarron, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrow, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrow, Wilma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoge, Per, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyle, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrewster, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBronstein, Laura R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClemans, Allie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeery, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFenton, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlockling, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenaway, Lesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanna, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHannah, Elizabeth F.S, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHannah, Elizabeth F.S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodson, Ann V., econ